<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n06038l"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n06" href="#n06038l">N06 (VI.B.11)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n06all.htm#n06038l"> 38(l)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> bigs tout / puis pet&apos;t</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">L&apos;imagination de l&apos;enfant est essentiellement amplificative. Peut-&ecirc;tre est-ce une cons&eacute;quence de la comparaison qu&apos;il fait de ce qui l&apos;entoure avec lui-m&ecirc;me, qui est si petit, peut-&ecirc;tre aussi, et plus probablement, cela tient-il &agrave; son manque d&apos;exp&eacute;rience &hellip;, mais, personnes et choses, <mark>il voit tout en grand</mark>. &hellip; Telle est la raison pour laquelle le souvenir des lieux o&ugrave; s&apos;est &eacute;coul&eacute;e notre enfance, concorde si peu avec la r&eacute;alit&eacute;. Bien qu&apos;ils soient rest&eacute;s les m&ecirc;mes, nous sommes, plus tard, tout &eacute;tonn&eacute;s de les trouver si diff&eacute;rents; <mark>tout semble diminu&eacute;</mark> &hellip;. <font color="green">[The imagination of the child is essentially amplifying. Perhaps this is a consequence of comparing what is around him to himself, which is so small, perhaps also, and more likely, is it due to his lack of experience &hellip; but, people and things, he sees everything big. This is the reason why the memory of the places where our childhood has passed, agrees so little with the reality. Although they remained the same, we are, later, quite surprised to find them so different; everything seems diminished]</font> <small> Fr&eacute;d&eacute;ric Queyrat, <a name="FQLJ" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#FQLJ"><cite title="source">Les Jeux des Enfants</cite></a> (1920) 6</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
